# Using mae (Cursor)

This project uses the **mae** spec-driven development workflow. This rule is always on — it
is the contract you follow before doing anything else.

**The rule.** If there is a ≥1% chance a workflow command applies to what you are doing,
follow it before any response — including clarifying questions. Re-read the command file
each time; do not rely on memory.

## Entry points

Feature and bug work enters **only** through `/mae-start` and `/mae-fix`. `/mae-init`
bootstraps or adopts a project and surveys it (one-time; re-run to refresh the map);
`/mae-finish` reviews and closes. A trivial change takes the light route — size routing is
legitimate, announced out loud, never smuggled.

## How process discipline is applied

mae owns the SDD layer. Cursor has no plugin system, no dispatchable subagents, and no
plan-approval tool, so the discipline is **inlined** into each command — you perform it
yourself, in the main context:

| mae stage | what you do inline |
|---|---|
| planning | write the plan to `specs/<feature>/plan.md`, **present it and STOP** — no code until the user replies `approved` |
| implementation | write the failing test first, then the smallest code that greens it |
| diagnosis (`/mae-fix`) | reproduce → root-cause → fix; never guess a patch from the symptom |
| completion gate (`/mae-finish`) | evidence before claims — every checked item traces to captured command output |
| review loop (`/mae-finish`) | review the diff (design, readability, security, performance, testability + the hard rules), then react to findings |
| workspace isolation | optional: work in a git worktree if you want to keep the current tree untouched |

## Precedence

These stages run **inside** mae commands, never as entry points. If you feel the urge to
"just start planning" or "just start coding" on feature work, route to `/mae-start` (or
`/mae-fix` for a bug) instead — it sequences the stages at the right time.

## Interview doctrine (ask when uncertain)

Design decisions belong to the user. Ask **one question at a time**, each with your
recommended answer and a one-line why. Research facts from the code and docs; ask only
genuine decisions. No execution before shared understanding is confirmed.

## Three documents, never one

`docs/constitution.md` is engineering law; `docs/PROJECT.md` is business context;
`docs/architecture-map.md` is the structural map. They are three different documents and
all are required — never fold one into another.
